stylometry: Decision theory includes the components of all possible/available options. Secondly, it provides all variables with the options and the probability of the decision-outcomes that come along. Thirdly, it gives us the analysis of figures that comes with the probabilities. In other words - the payoff table. All the positive factors in the payoff table are the rewards (or, gains), and all the negatives are the costs (or, losses). We can only choose the rows we would want, but not the columns. In other words the "best" decision we make, can still have unwanted factors - but it doesn't make the decision the wrong, or bad one.
